TITLE: UK brings budget forward in another attempt to reassure markets
SUMMARY: UK Finance Minister Kwasi Kwarteng will publish details of his plans to tackle ballooning government debt and kickstart economic growth on October 31, more than three weeks earlier than scheduled, in an attempt to reassure investors and restore the government's badly damaged credibility.

TITLE: The nation's gun control laws have been put in jeopardy
SUMMARY: It did not take long for top gun rights activists to realize that the Second Amendment ruling handed down by the Supreme Court in June was going to transform the legal fight over access to firearms.

TITLE: El Paso's new dashboard shows the thousands of migrants it serves and how many it sends north
SUMMARY: Amid a spike in migrant encounters at the southern border, the City of El Paso, Texas, launched a migrant dashboard Saturday to follow activity at its welcome center.

TITLE: Two brothers arrested in connection to kidnapping and killing of a California family
SUMMARY: A community in central California is grappling with the grief of losing an 8-month old baby, her parents and her uncle, who were kidnapped and killed earlier this week allegedly by a former employee of their family-owned business.

TITLE: Law school mistakenly sent out 4,000 acceptance letters
SUMMARY: Over 200 law school applicants received the exciting news that they had been accepted to Northeastern University's law school last week. There was just one problem: The acceptance letters were sent by mistake, according to the university.

TITLE: NYC mayor declares state of emergency over influx of migrants
SUMMARY: Mayor Eric Adams has declared a state of emergency to help respond to the city's migrant crisis, which he told reporters Friday will cost the city $1 billion this fiscal year.

TITLE: Glenn Youngkin defends support of election denier Kari Lake in Arizona
SUMMARY: Virginia Gov. Glenn Youngkin on Sunday defended his support for fellow Republican Kari Lake, an election denier running for governor in Arizona, arguing that their party needs to be inclusive of a wide range of members in order to be successful.

TITLE: Slotkin calls for 'new blood' in Democratic Party but says she will support Biden if he runs in 2024
SUMMARY: Democratic Rep. Elissa Slotkin of Michigan said Sunday the Democratic Party needs "new blood" in Washington, but emphasized her support for President Joe Biden if he decides to run for reelection.

TITLE: Warnock says Walker 'has trouble with the truth' but does not comment on abortion allegations
SUMMARY: Democratic Sen. Raphael Warnock of Georgia said Saturday that his Republican rival Herschel Walker "has trouble with the truth" but did not directly address the recent allegation that Walker once paid for a woman to have an abortion.

TITLE: Biden's marijuana pardon: Who isn't eligible?
SUMMARY: President Joe Biden announced on Thursday that he's pardoning individuals charged with simple marijuana possession on a federal level, but his decision does not affect broad groups of Americans and non-citizens charged with the crime.

TITLE: Federal prosecutors weighing charges on two fronts in Hunter Biden investigation
SUMMARY: Federal prosecutors believe they could charge Hunter Biden with tax crimes and a false statement but a final decision still has not yet been made by the US attorney in Delaware, according to sources familiar with the matter.

TITLE: Study shows Chick-fil-A has the slowest drive-thru. Here's why
SUMMARY: Every second counts in drive-thru lanes for fast food chains. A recent study showed Chick-fil-A had the slowest one â€” but only because it's so popular and there are so many cars in line.

TITLE: Customers turn away from mainstream grocers
SUMMARY: With grocery prices soaring, consumers are changing the way they shop for food. That's great news for discount grocers like bare-bones supermarket Aldi.

TITLE: China's holiday spending plunges to seven-year low as zero-Covid batters consumer confidence
SUMMARY: Holiday spending during China's Golden Week has plunged to its lowest level in seven years, as broad Covid curbs discouraged people from traveling or spending, while a darkening economic outlook continues to erode consumer confidence.
